{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Enable and enforce host confinement via AppArmor (or equivalent MAC) profiles for service and agent processes to strictly limit filesystem access, prevent access to staging directories, and block unauthorized network socket creation.",
  "comments": "I added and enforced AppArmor profiles for the agent binary (/usr/src/app/splunkd), shell (/bin/sh), and common exfil tools (/bin/cp, /bin/tar, /usr/bin/curl). Profiles explicitly deny access to the attacker's staging directory (/usr/src/app/staged and staged.tar.gz) and include network socket denies for those utilities. AppArmor profiles are loaded and in enforce mode as shown by aa-status. This significantly reduces the attacker's ability to use the observed workflow (find/cp/tar/curl) to collect, archive, and exfiltrate files while keeping the host online (meeting live-response constraints). Important next steps: (1) verify denials in dmesg or /var/log/kern.log when re-running the attack to confirm AppArmor blocked file reads or network sockets, (2) ensure nftables/perimeter egress controls remain active (default-deny OUTPUT allowing only proxy/DNS), (3) expand profiles for any additional tools observed, (4) persist and protect profiles, and (5) collect AppArmor and nft logs as forensics. Note: an attacker with root can still attempt to bypass LSMs; combine these host controls with network-layer blocking (nftables, firewall, Snort) for defense-in-depth.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "cat > /etc/apparmor.d/bin.sh << 'EOF' ... EOF",
    "apparmor_parser -r /etc/apparmor.d/bin.sh || true",
    "aa-status || true"
  ]
}
